and indoors, Getting Past 'the Pimp' incorporates solid empirical evidence including documentary analysis, 75 interviews with third parties, and 52 interviews with sex workers to unpack the roles and relationships of third parties in three sectors of the sex industry‒ incall/outcall, stripping, and street-based prostitution. Contrary to prevailing stereotypes that portray third parties as inherently abusive and controlling, these workers fulfill important roles and provide vital services as associates, fee-for-service hires, and agency owners or managers responsible for scheduling and arranging transportation and security. The sex industry, like mainstream businesses, rarely depend exclusively on client and worker to operate efficiently, and safely.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aPimps. 0aProstitution. 0aSex-oriented businesses. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh1 aBruckert, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClamen, Jenn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorriveau, Patrice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJeffrey, Leslie Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaw, Tuulia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMensah, Maria Nengeh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParent, Colette , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aParent, Colette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060679940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751741040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487517410423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487517410.jpg  